\title{Clinical Decision Support}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{"Generate professional clinical decision support (CDS) documents for pharmaceutical and clinical research settings, including patient cohort analyses (biomarker-stratified with outcomes) and treatment recommendation reports (evidence-based guidelines with decision algorithms). Supports GRADE evidence grading, statistical analysis (hazard ratios, survival curves, waterfall plots), biomarker integration, and regulatory compliance. Outputs publication-ready LaTeX/PDF format optimized for drug development, clinical research, and evidence synthesis."}

\subtree{
\title{Clinical Decision Support Documents}
\subtree{
\title{Description}
\p{Generate professional clinical decision support (CDS) documents for pharmaceutical companies, clinical researchers, and medical decision-makers. This skill specializes in analytical, evidence-based documents that inform treatment strategies and drug development:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Patient Cohort Analysis} - Biomarker-stratified group analyses with statistical outcome comparisons}
\li{\strong{Treatment Recommendation Reports} - Evidence-based clinical guidelines with GRADE grading and decision algorithms}
}

\p{All documents are generated as publication-ready LaTeX/PDF files optimized for pharmaceutical research, regulatory submissions, and clinical guideline development.}

\p{\strong{Note:} For individual patient treatment plans at the bedside, use the \code{\startverb treatment-plans\stopverb} skill instead. This skill focuses on group-level analyses and evidence synthesis for pharmaceutical/research settings.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Capabilities}
\subtree{
\title{Document Types}
\p{\strong{Patient Cohort Analysis}}

\ul{
\li{Biomarker-based patient stratification (molecular subtypes, gene expression, IHC)}
\li{Molecular subtype classification (e.g., GBM mesenchymal-immune-active vs proneural, breast cancer subtypes)}
\li{Outcome metrics with statistical analysis (OS, PFS, ORR, DOR, DCR)}
\li{Statistical comparisons between subgroups (hazard ratios, p-values, 95\% CI)}
\li{Survival analysis with Kaplan-Meier curves and log-rank tests}
\li{Efficacy tables and waterfall plots}
\li{Comparative effectiveness analyses}
\li{Pharmaceutical cohort reporting (trial subgroups, real-world evidence)}
}

\p{\strong{Treatment Recommendation Reports}}

\ul{
\li{Evidence-based treatment guidelines for specific disease states}
\li{Strength of recommendation grading (GRADE system: 1A, 1B, 2A, 2B, 2C)}
\li{Quality of evidence assessment (high, moderate, low, very low)}
\li{Treatment algorithm flowcharts with TikZ diagrams}
\li{Line-of-therapy sequencing based on biomarkers}
\li{Decision pathways with clinical and molecular criteria}
\li{Pharmaceutical strategy documents}
\li{Clinical guideline development for medical societies}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Clinical Features}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Biomarker Integration}: Genomic alterations (mutations, CNV, fusions), gene expression signatures, IHC markers, PD-L1 scoring}
\li{\strong{Statistical Analysis}: Hazard ratios, p-values, confidence intervals, survival curves, Cox regression, log-rank tests}
\li{\strong{Evidence Grading}: GRADE system (1A/1B/2A/2B/2C), Oxford CEBM levels, quality of evidence assessment}
\li{\strong{Clinical Terminology}: SNOMED-CT, LOINC, proper medical nomenclature, trial nomenclature}
\li{\strong{Regulatory Compliance}: HIPAA de-identification, confidentiality headers, ICH-GCP alignment}
\li{\strong{Professional Formatting}: Compact 0.5in margins, color-coded recommendations, publication-ready, suitable for regulatory submissions}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Pharmaceutical and Research Use Cases}
\p{This skill is specifically designed for pharmaceutical and clinical research applications:}

\p{\strong{Drug Development}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Phase 2/3 Trial Analyses}: Biomarker-stratified efficacy and safety analyses}
\li{\strong{Subgroup Analyses}: Forest plots showing treatment effects across patient subgroups}
\li{\strong{Companion Diagnostic Development}: Linking biomarkers to drug response}
\li{\strong{Regulatory Submissions}: IND/NDA documentation with evidence summaries}
}

\p{\strong{Medical Affairs}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{KOL Education Materials}: Evidence-based treatment algorithms for thought leaders}
\li{\strong{Medical Strategy Documents}: Competitive landscape and positioning strategies}
\li{\strong{Advisory Board Materials}: Cohort analyses and treatment recommendation frameworks}
\li{\strong{Publication Planning}: Manuscript-ready analyses for peer-reviewed journals}
}

\p{\strong{Clinical Guidelines}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Guideline Development}: Evidence synthesis with GRADE methodology for specialty societies}
\li{\strong{Consensus Recommendations}: Multi-stakeholder treatment algorithm development}
\li{\strong{Practice Standards}: Biomarker-based treatment selection criteria}
\li{\strong{Quality Measures}: Evidence-based performance metrics}
}

\p{\strong{Real-World Evidence}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{RWE Cohort Studies}: Retrospective analyses of patient cohorts from EMR data}
\li{\strong{Comparative Effectiveness}: Head-to-head treatment comparisons in real-world settings}
\li{\strong{Outcomes Research}: Long-term survival and safety in clinical practice}
\li{\strong{Health Economics}: Cost-effectiveness analyses by biomarker subgroup}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\p{Use this skill when you need to:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Analyze patient cohorts} stratified by biomarkers, molecular subtypes, or clinical characteristics}
\li{\strong{Generate treatment recommendation reports} with evidence grading for clinical guidelines or pharmaceutical strategies}
\li{\strong{Compare outcomes} between patient subgroups with statistical analysis (survival, response rates, hazard ratios)}
\li{\strong{Produce pharmaceutical research documents} for drug development, clinical trials, or regulatory submissions}
\li{\strong{Develop clinical practice guidelines} with GRADE evidence grading and decision algorithms}
\li{\strong{Document biomarker-guided therapy selection} at the population level (not individual patients)}
\li{\strong{Synthesize evidence} from multiple trials or real-world data sources}
\li{\strong{Create clinical decision algorithms} with flowcharts for treatment sequencing}
}

\p{\strong{Do NOT use this skill for:}}

\ul{
\li{Individual patient treatment plans (use \code{\startverb treatment-plans\stopverb} skill)}
\li{Bedside clinical care documentation (use \code{\startverb treatment-plans\stopverb} skill)}
\li{Simple patient-specific treatment protocols (use \code{\startverb treatment-plans\stopverb} skill)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Visual Enhancement with Scientific Schematics}
\p{\strong{⚠️ MANDATORY: Every clinical decision support document MUST include at least 1-2 AI-generated figures using the scientific-schematics skill.}}

\p{This is not optional. Clinical decision documents require clear visual algorithms. Before finalizing any document:}

\ol{
\li{Generate at minimum ONE schematic or diagram (e.g., clinical decision algorithm, treatment pathway, or biomarker stratification tree)}
\li{For cohort analyses: include patient flow diagram}
\li{For treatment recommendations: include decision flowchart}
}

\p{\strong{How to generate figures:}}

\ul{
\li{Use the \strong{scientific-schematics} skill to generate AI-powered publication-quality diagrams}
\li{Simply describe your desired diagram in natural language}
\li{Nano Banana Pro will automatically generate, review, and refine the schematic}
}

\p{\strong{How to generate schematics:}}

\pre{\startverb
python scripts/generate_schematic.py "your diagram description" -o figures/output.png
\stopverb}

\p{The AI will automatically:}

\ul{
\li{Create publication-quality images with proper formatting}
\li{Review and refine through multiple iterations}
\li{Ensure accessibility (colorblind-friendly, high contrast)}
\li{Save outputs in the figures/ directory}
}

\p{\strong{When to add schematics:}}

\ul{
\li{Clinical decision algorithm flowcharts}
\li{Treatment pathway diagrams}
\li{Biomarker stratification trees}
\li{Patient cohort flow diagrams (CONSORT-style)}
\li{Survival curve visualizations}
\li{Molecular mechanism diagrams}
\li{Any complex concept that benefits from visualization}
}

\p{For detailed guidance on creating schematics, refer to the scientific-schematics skill documentation.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Document Structure}
\p{\strong{CRITICAL REQUIREMENT: All clinical decision support documents MUST begin with a complete executive summary on page 1 that spans the entire first page before any table of contents or detailed sections.}}

\subtree{
\title{Page 1 Executive Summary Structure}
\p{The first page of every CDS document should contain ONLY the executive summary with the following components:}

\p{\strong{Required Elements (all on page 1):}}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Document Title and Type}}
\li{Main title (e.g., "Biomarker-Stratified Cohort Analysis" or "Evidence-Based Treatment Recommendations")}
\li{Subtitle with disease state and focus}
\li{\strong{Report Information Box} (using colored tcolorbox)}
\li{Document type and purpose}
\li{Date of analysis/report}
\li{Disease state and patient population}
\li{Author/institution (if applicable)}
\li{Analysis framework or methodology}
\li{\strong{Key Findings Boxes} (3-5 colored boxes using tcolorbox)}
\li{\strong{Primary Results} (blue box): Main efficacy/outcome findings}
\li{\strong{Biomarker Insights} (green box): Key molecular subtype findings}
\li{\strong{Clinical Implications} (yellow/orange box): Actionable treatment implications}
\li{\strong{Statistical Summary} (gray box): Hazard ratios, p-values, key statistics}
\li{\strong{Safety Highlights} (red box, if applicable): Critical adverse events or warnings}
}

\p{\strong{Visual Requirements:}}

\ul{
\li{Use \code{\startverb \startverb \thispagestyle\stopverb{empty}\stopverb} to remove page numbers from page 1}
\li{All content must fit on page 1 (before \code{\startverb \startverb \newpage\stopverb\stopverb})}
\li{Use colored tcolorbox environments with different colors for visual hierarchy}
\li{Boxes should be scannable and highlight most critical information}
\li{Use bullet points, not narrative paragraphs}
\li{End page 1 with \code{\startverb \startverb \newpage\stopverb\stopverb} before table of contents or detailed sections}
}

\p{\strong{Example First Page LaTeX Structure:}}

\pre{\startverb
\maketitle
\thispagestyle{empty}

% Report Information Box
\begin{tcolorbox}[colback=blue!5!white, colframe=blue!75!black, title=Report Information]
\textbf{Document Type:} Patient Cohort Analysis\\
\textbf{Disease State:} HER2-Positive Metastatic Breast Cancer\\
\textbf{Analysis Date:} \today\\
\textbf{Population:} 60 patients, biomarker-stratified by HR status
\end{tcolorbox}

\vspace{0.3cm}

% Key Finding #1: Primary Results
\begin{tcolorbox}[colback=blue!5!white, colframe=blue!75!black, title=Primary Efficacy Results]
\begin{itemize}
    \item Overall ORR: 72\% (95\% CI: 59-83\%)
    \item Median PFS: 18.5 months (95\% CI: 14.2-22.8)
    \item Median OS: 35.2 months (95\% CI: 28.1-NR)
\end{itemize}
\end{tcolorbox}

\vspace{0.3cm}

% Key Finding #2: Biomarker Insights
\begin{tcolorbox}[colback=green!5!white, colframe=green!75!black, title=Biomarker Stratification Findings]
\begin{itemize}
    \item HR+/HER2+: ORR 68\%, median PFS 16.2 months
    \item HR-/HER2+: ORR 78\%, median PFS 22.1 months
    \item HR status significantly associated with outcomes (p=0.041)
\end{itemize}
\end{tcolorbox}

\vspace{0.3cm}

% Key Finding #3: Clinical Implications
\begin{tcolorbox}[colback=orange!5!white, colframe=orange!75!black, title=Clinical Recommendations]
\begin{itemize}
    \item Strong efficacy observed regardless of HR status (Grade 1A)
    \item HR-/HER2+ patients showed numerically superior outcomes
    \item Treatment recommended for all HER2+ MBC patients
\end{itemize}
\end{tcolorbox}

\newpage
\tableofcontents  % TOC on page 2
\newpage  % Detailed content starts page 3
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Patient Cohort Analysis (Detailed Sections - Page 3+)}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Cohort Characteristics}: Demographics, baseline features, patient selection criteria}
\li{\strong{Biomarker Stratification}: Molecular subtypes, genomic alterations, IHC profiles}
\li{\strong{Treatment Exposure}: Therapies received, dosing, treatment duration by subgroup}
\li{\strong{Outcome Analysis}: Response rates (ORR, DCR), survival data (OS, PFS), DOR}
\li{\strong{Statistical Methods}: Kaplan-Meier survival curves, hazard ratios, log-rank tests, Cox regression}
\li{\strong{Subgroup Comparisons}: Biomarker-stratified efficacy, forest plots, statistical significance}
\li{\strong{Safety Profile}: Adverse events by subgroup, dose modifications, discontinuations}
\li{\strong{Clinical Recommendations}: Treatment implications based on biomarker profiles}
\li{\strong{Figures}: Waterfall plots, swimmer plots, survival curves, forest plots}
\li{\strong{Tables}: Demographics table, biomarker frequency, outcomes by subgroup}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Treatment Recommendation Reports (Detailed Sections - Page 3+)}
\p{\strong{Page 1 Executive Summary for Treatment Recommendations should include:}}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Report Information Box}: Disease state, guideline version/date, target population}
\li{\strong{Key Recommendations Box} (green): Top 3-5 GRADE-graded recommendations by line of therapy}
\li{\strong{Biomarker Decision Criteria Box} (blue): Key molecular markers influencing treatment selection}
\li{\strong{Evidence Summary Box} (gray): Major trials supporting recommendations (e.g., KEYNOTE-189, FLAURA)}
\li{\strong{Critical Monitoring Box} (orange/red): Essential safety monitoring requirements}
}

\p{\strong{Detailed Sections (Page 3+):}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Clinical Context}: Disease state, epidemiology, current treatment landscape}
\li{\strong{Target Population}: Patient characteristics, biomarker criteria, staging}
\li{\strong{Evidence Review}: Systematic literature synthesis, guideline summary, trial data}
\li{\strong{Treatment Options}: Available therapies with mechanism of action}
\li{\strong{Evidence Grading}: GRADE assessment for each recommendation (1A, 1B, 2A, 2B, 2C)}
\li{\strong{Recommendations by Line}: First-line, second-line, subsequent therapies}
\li{\strong{Biomarker-Guided Selection}: Decision criteria based on molecular profiles}
\li{\strong{Treatment Algorithms}: TikZ flowcharts showing decision pathways}
\li{\strong{Monitoring Protocol}: Safety assessments, efficacy monitoring, dose modifications}
\li{\strong{Special Populations}: Elderly, renal/hepatic impairment, comorbidities}
\li{\strong{References}: Full bibliography with trial names and citations}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Output Format}
\p{\strong{MANDATORY FIRST PAGE REQUIREMENT:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Page 1}: Full-page executive summary with 3-5 colored tcolorbox elements}
\li{\strong{Page 2}: Table of contents (optional)}
\li{\strong{Page 3+}: Detailed sections with methods, results, figures, tables}
}

\p{\strong{Document Specifications:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Primary}: LaTeX/PDF with 0.5in margins for compact, data-dense presentation}
\li{\strong{Length}: Typically 5-15 pages (1 page executive summary + 4-14 pages detailed content)}
\li{\strong{Style}: Publication-ready, pharmaceutical-grade, suitable for regulatory submissions}
\li{\strong{First Page}: Always a complete executive summary spanning entire page 1 (see Document Structure section)}
}

\p{\strong{Visual Elements:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Colors}: }
\li{Page 1 boxes: blue=data/information, green=biomarkers/recommendations, yellow/orange=clinical implications, red=warnings}
\li{Recommendation boxes (green=strong recommendation, yellow=conditional, blue=research needed)}
\li{Biomarker stratification (color-coded molecular subtypes)}
\li{Statistical significance (color-coded p-values, hazard ratios)}
\li{\strong{Tables}: }
\li{Demographics with baseline characteristics}
\li{Biomarker frequency by subgroup}
\li{Outcomes table (ORR, PFS, OS, DOR by molecular subtype)}
\li{Adverse events by cohort}
\li{Evidence summary tables with GRADE ratings}
\li{\strong{Figures}: }
\li{Kaplan-Meier survival curves with log-rank p-values and number at risk tables}
\li{Waterfall plots showing best response by patient}
\li{Forest plots for subgroup analyses with confidence intervals}
\li{TikZ decision algorithm flowcharts}
\li{Swimmer plots for individual patient timelines}
\li{\strong{Statistics}: Hazard ratios with 95\% CI, p-values, median survival times, landmark survival rates}
\li{\strong{Compliance}: De-identification per HIPAA Safe Harbor, confidentiality notices for proprietary data}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Integration}
\p{This skill integrates with:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{scientific-writing}: Citation management, statistical reporting, evidence synthesis}
\li{\strong{clinical-reports}: Medical terminology, HIPAA compliance, regulatory documentation}
\li{\strong{scientific-schematics}: TikZ flowcharts for decision algorithms and treatment pathways}
\li{\strong{treatment-plans}: Individual patient applications of cohort-derived insights (bidirectional)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Key Differentiators from Treatment-Plans Skill}
\p{\strong{Clinical Decision Support (this skill):}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Audience}: Pharmaceutical companies, clinical researchers, guideline committees, medical affairs}
\li{\strong{Scope}: Population-level analyses, evidence synthesis, guideline development}
\li{\strong{Focus}: Biomarker stratification, statistical comparisons, evidence grading}
\li{\strong{Output}: Multi-page analytical documents (5-15 pages typical) with extensive figures and tables}
\li{\strong{Use Cases}: Drug development, regulatory submissions, clinical practice guidelines, medical strategy}
\li{\strong{Example}: "Analyze 60 HER2+ breast cancer patients by hormone receptor status with survival outcomes"}
}

\p{\strong{Treatment-Plans Skill:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Audience}: Clinicians, patients, care teams}
\li{\strong{Scope}: Individual patient care planning}
\li{\strong{Focus}: SMART goals, patient-specific interventions, monitoring plans}
\li{\strong{Output}: Concise 1-4 page actionable care plans}
\li{\strong{Use Cases}: Bedside clinical care, EMR documentation, patient-centered planning}
\li{\strong{Example}: "Create treatment plan for a 55-year-old patient with newly diagnosed type 2 diabetes"}
}

\p{\strong{When to use each:}}

\ul{
\li{Use \strong{clinical-decision-support} for: cohort analyses, biomarker stratification studies, treatment guideline development, pharmaceutical strategy documents}
\li{Use \strong{treatment-plans} for: individual patient care plans, treatment protocols for specific patients, bedside clinical documentation}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Example Usage}
\subtree{
\title{Patient Cohort Analysis}
\p{\strong{Example 1: NSCLC Biomarker Stratification}}

\pre{\startverb
> Analyze a cohort of 45 NSCLC patients stratified by PD-L1 expression (<1%, 1-49%, ≥50%) 
> receiving pembrolizumab. Include outcomes: ORR, median PFS, median OS with hazard ratios 
> comparing PD-L1 ≥50% vs <50%. Generate Kaplan-Meier curves and waterfall plot.
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Example 2: GBM Molecular Subtype Analysis}}

\pre{\startverb
> Generate cohort analysis for 30 GBM patients classified into Cluster 1 (Mesenchymal-Immune-Active) 
> and Cluster 2 (Proneural) molecular subtypes. Compare outcomes including median OS, 6-month PFS rate, 
> and response to TMZ+bevacizumab. Include biomarker profile table and statistical comparison.
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Example 3: Breast Cancer HER2 Cohort}}

\pre{\startverb
> Analyze 60 HER2-positive metastatic breast cancer patients treated with trastuzumab-deruxtecan, 
> stratified by prior trastuzumab exposure (yes/no). Include ORR, DOR, median PFS with forest plot 
> showing subgroup analyses by hormone receptor status, brain metastases, and number of prior lines.
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Treatment Recommendation Report}
\p{\strong{Example 1: HER2+ Metastatic Breast Cancer Guidelines}}

\pre{\startverb
> Create evidence-based treatment recommendations for HER2-positive metastatic breast cancer including 
> biomarker-guided therapy selection. Use GRADE system to grade recommendations for first-line 
> (trastuzumab+pertuzumab+taxane), second-line (trastuzumab-deruxtecan), and third-line options. 
> Include decision algorithm flowchart based on brain metastases, hormone receptor status, and prior therapies.
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Example 2: Advanced NSCLC Treatment Algorithm}}

\pre{\startverb
> Generate treatment recommendation report for advanced NSCLC based on PD-L1 expression, EGFR mutation, 
> ALK rearrangement, and performance status. Include GRADE-graded recommendations for each molecular subtype, 
> TikZ flowchart for biomarker-directed therapy selection, and evidence tables from KEYNOTE-189, FLAURA, 
> and CheckMate-227 trials.
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Example 3: Multiple Myeloma Line-of-Therapy Sequencing}}

\pre{\startverb
> Create treatment algorithm for newly diagnosed multiple myeloma through relapsed/refractory setting. 
> Include GRADE recommendations for transplant-eligible vs ineligible, high-risk cytogenetics considerations, 
> and sequencing of daratumumab, carfilzomib, and CAR-T therapy. Provide flowchart showing decision points 
> at each line of therapy.
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Key Features}
\subtree{
\title{Biomarker Classification}
\ul{
\li{Genomic: Mutations, CNV, gene fusions}
\li{Expression: RNA-seq, IHC scores}
\li{Molecular subtypes: Disease-specific classifications}
\li{Clinical actionability: Therapy selection guidance}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Outcome Metrics}
\ul{
\li{Survival: OS (overall survival), PFS (progression-free survival)}
\li{Response: ORR (objective response rate), DOR (duration of response), DCR (disease control rate)}
\li{Quality: ECOG performance status, symptom burden}
\li{Safety: Adverse events, dose modifications}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Statistical Methods}
\ul{
\li{Survival analysis: Kaplan-Meier curves, log-rank tests}
\li{Group comparisons: t-tests, chi-square, Fisher's exact}
\li{Effect sizes: Hazard ratios, odds ratios with 95\% CI}
\li{Significance: p-values, multiple testing corrections}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Evidence Grading}
\p{\strong{GRADE System}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{1A}: Strong recommendation, high-quality evidence}
\li{\strong{1B}: Strong recommendation, moderate-quality evidence  }
\li{\strong{2A}: Weak recommendation, high-quality evidence}
\li{\strong{2B}: Weak recommendation, moderate-quality evidence}
\li{\strong{2C}: Weak recommendation, low-quality evidence}
}

\p{\strong{Recommendation Strength}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Strong}: Benefits clearly outweigh risks}
\li{\strong{Conditional}: Trade-offs exist, patient values important}
\li{\strong{Research}: Insufficient evidence, clinical trials needed}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Best Practices}
\subtree{
\title{For Cohort Analyses}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Patient Selection Transparency}: Clearly document inclusion/exclusion criteria, patient flow, and reasons for exclusions}
\li{\strong{Biomarker Clarity}: Specify assay methods, platforms (e.g., FoundationOne, Caris), cut-points, and validation status}
\li{\strong{Statistical Rigor}: }
\li{Report hazard ratios with 95\% confidence intervals, not just p-values}
\li{Include median follow-up time for survival analyses}
\li{Specify statistical tests used (log-rank, Cox regression, Fisher's exact)}
\li{Account for multiple comparisons when appropriate}
\li{\strong{Outcome Definitions}: Use standard criteria:}
\li{Response: RECIST 1.1, iRECIST for immunotherapy}
\li{Adverse events: CTCAE version 5.0}
\li{Performance status: ECOG or Karnofsky}
\li{\strong{Survival Data Presentation}:}
\li{Median OS/PFS with 95\% CI}
\li{Landmark survival rates (6-month, 12-month, 24-month)}
\li{Number at risk tables below Kaplan-Meier curves}
\li{Censoring clearly indicated}
\li{\strong{Subgroup Analyses}: Pre-specify subgroups; clearly label exploratory vs pre-planned analyses}
\li{\strong{Data Completeness}: Report missing data and how it was handled}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{For Treatment Recommendation Reports}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Evidence Grading Transparency}: }
\li{Use GRADE system consistently (1A, 1B, 2A, 2B, 2C)}
\li{Document rationale for each grade}
\li{Clearly state quality of evidence (high, moderate, low, very low)}
\li{\strong{Comprehensive Evidence Review}: }
\li{Include phase 3 randomized trials as primary evidence}
\li{Supplement with phase 2 data for emerging therapies}
\li{Note real-world evidence and meta-analyses}
\li{Cite trial names (e.g., KEYNOTE-189, CheckMate-227)}
\li{\strong{Biomarker-Guided Recommendations}:}
\li{Link specific biomarkers to therapy recommendations}
\li{Specify testing methods and validated assays}
\li{Include FDA/EMA approval status for companion diagnostics}
\li{\strong{Clinical Actionability}: Every recommendation should have clear implementation guidance}
\li{\strong{Decision Algorithm Clarity}: TikZ flowcharts should be unambiguous with clear yes/no decision points}
\li{\strong{Special Populations}: Address elderly, renal/hepatic impairment, pregnancy, drug interactions}
\li{\strong{Monitoring Guidance}: Specify safety labs, imaging, and frequency}
\li{\strong{Update Frequency}: Date recommendations and plan for periodic updates}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{General Best Practices}
\ol{
\li{\strong{First Page Executive Summary (MANDATORY)}: }
\li{ALWAYS create a complete executive summary on page 1 that spans the entire first page}
\li{Use 3-5 colored tcolorbox elements to highlight key findings}
\li{No table of contents or detailed sections on page 1}
\li{Use \code{\startverb \startverb \thispagestyle\stopverb{empty}\stopverb} and end with \code{\startverb \startverb \newpage\stopverb\stopverb}}
\li{This is the single most important page - it should be scannable in 60 seconds}
\li{\strong{De-identification}: Remove all 18 HIPAA identifiers before document generation (Safe Harbor method)}
\li{\strong{Regulatory Compliance}: Include confidentiality notices for proprietary pharmaceutical data}
\li{\strong{Publication-Ready Formatting}: Use 0.5in margins, professional fonts, color-coded sections}
\li{\strong{Reproducibility}: Document all statistical methods to enable replication}
\li{\strong{Conflict of Interest}: Disclose pharmaceutical funding or relationships when applicable}
\li{\strong{Visual Hierarchy}: Use colored boxes consistently (blue=data, green=biomarkers, yellow/orange=recommendations, red=warnings)}
}
}
}

